Example dataset

Lets assume that we are interested in knowing whether homework helps ones learning experience. Research question is Does math homework help ones school performance?.

Datafile (L1.txt) contains two variables, mathhome and mathach. Two variables are 1) mathhome (IV, X): time spent on math homework per week (in hours), and 2) mathach (DV, Y): math achievement test score (T scores, M = 50, SD = 10).

> # Read dataset and save it as "l1". 
> l1=read.table("l1.txt", sep="", header=TRUE, quote="\"'")
>

> # Slope (b1) is 1.99, which is the unstandardized slope for the IV. It indicates that the amount of change expected 
> # in mathach when the number of hours of studying per week increases by 1 hour is 1.99. 
> # Intercept (b0) is 47.03 (as shown in the row labeled as intercept). It indicates that the best predicted score 
> #when the time spent on math homework per week is zero is 47.03. 
> 
> # The overall model is statistically significant (F(1,98) = 11.2, p = .002). 
> #The R-squared value of .10 suggests that 10% of variance in math achievement was explained by time spent on homework per week. 
> 
>

WRITE-UP

The overall model is statistically significant (F(1,98) = 11.2, p = .002). The R-squared value of .10 suggests that 10% of variance in math achievement was explained by time spent on homework per week. The estimated slope is 1.99 (SE = .60), which is statistically significant (t(98)= 3.34, p < .01). This indicates that math homework is expected to increase by 1.99 of a score on math achievement, for every additional hour spent on homework. The estimated intercept is 47.03 (SE = 1.69), which is statistically significant (t(98) = 27.76, p < .01). The expected math achievement is 47.03, when the time spent on math homework per week is 0.
